<TITLE> European stocks hit day's highs on US price data </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, July 31 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European stocks briefly extended gains on Tuesday and hit session highs after core US consumer prices rose a less-than-expected 0.1 percent in June, supporting market views that US rates are unlikely to rise soon. Analysts polled by Reuters were expecting the core price index to gain 0.2 percent on the month. U.S. stock index futures also extended gains. By 1240 GMT, the FTSEurofirst 300 index of leading European shares was 2.0 percent higher at 1,547.9 after having risen as much as 2.2 percent to a session high of 1,550.6, its largest one-day gain since July 19 2006. The index had fallen for five straight trading sessions by Monday and is still 5 percent below a 6-1/2-year high of 1,635.6 hit on July 
